        "arm_group": {
            "arm_group_label": "Minimally invasive Approach", 
            "description": "Patients with a thoracolumbar Fracture A3.1 to A 3.3 treated by fracture fixation by a minimally invasive approach"
        }, 
        "brief_summary": {
            "textblock": "Spinal injuries, such as vertebral fractures, often result in a significant instability of\n      the spine and lead to acute or delayed neurological deficits. Depending on the type of\n      injury there are various methods available to stabilize the spine. The proposed study should\n      clarify whether the combined reduction and fixation with a minimally invasive approach can\n      actually be done with the same precision as in a conventional approach. The primary endpoint\n      of this investigation is the monosegmental anterior wedge angle (AWA), and its maintenance\n      over the first 6 postoperative weeks. It is the aim of the study to gather key radiological,\n      clinical and subjective patient outcome parameters for its patient population that will\n      allow to compare the results to a historical group of patients. The study design is\n      non-interventional, prospective, open,and multicentric."
        }, 
        "brief_title": "Minimally Invasive Reduction and Fixation of Thoracolumbar Fractures", 
        "completion_date": {
